	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You know, for the first few seconds when opening this thread, I actually thought it'd be about someone desperately wanting to get laid for the first time after spending too many years on video games. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=":wink:" title="Wink" /> 
<br />
<br />I'm with Tepples on the recommendation to start out with Python programming. It's a really nice high-level language, and you'll benefit immensely from learning it when you get to the point of needing to make tools for NES coding.
<br />
<br />On the other hand, this does not mean you will have to postpone learning to code 6502 on the NES. Memblers is a good example of someone who started learning 6502 on the NES as his first programming language ever. (and had he not, maybe we wouldn't be writing you these messages right now)
<br />
<br />My recommendation is to tackle this journey from two ends: use Python to learn about programming in general, and 6502+NES to learn about low-level hardware-oriented programming. In reality, these are two rather separate fields of software engineering. But at the same time, you'll sooner or later need to start thinking about how to apply what you learn from high-level software development to NES development in order to write maintainable code.
<br />
<br />What I would not recommend you though, is learning C/C++. This could very roughly be described as sitting right in the middle of an imaginary bar with Python on one end and 6502 on the other. While it's compromise between high-level and low-level programming has made it very successful in lots of areas (game programming for one), I reckon it'll be the worst of both worlds in your case. 
<br />
<br />If you'll get to the point of having a good understanding of both low-level AND high-level programming, then you will automatically see the use (and misuse) of C/C++ when you encounter it. But for now, keep these two fields of studies (high-level vs low-level programming) separated, but enjoy the learning experience from both,

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


